You can clone a repo on gitHub to allow you to work on it on your own laptop.
Get git from https://git-scm.com
Intall git for windows

Some commands:
git config  check a specific keys value
eg git config user.name returns 'Liz Hughes'
git help <verb> returns help documents
git add -h  returns a shortened version of help for the command add

On Git Bash (command line) navigate to the GitHub folder on your computer.
type 'git'
You should get lots of info showing git is corectly installrd.
If you get '-bash: git: command not found' git is not installed properly.
Using git locally with the command line is all about saying git <something>
eg git commit to make a commit.
In order to issue comands you need a folder on your computer that is a git repo
use git clone <repo url> to clone a repo from GitHub to locally on your computer.

'git status' shows you where your local copy is compared to the one on GitHub.
eg If I made changes to a file on my local copy these will be listed here.
'git commit' is not enough to make a commit. Commands need arguments.
'-a' stands for all, commit all changes
'-m' is for message and allows you to add a comment
'git log' allows you to see any commit locally
'git log -2' shows the last 2 commits
shift ; q gets you out of VIM
'git push' send things to GitHub
'Git pull' reciebve things from GitHub
'git remote' show you your remote server
'git remote -v' show the remote sever and url (-v means verbose). This allows you to check you are sending to the correct place.
To push a commit you need to specify the remote server and the branch you want to push to.
'git push origin main' to push from your local copy to the main branch in the original repo on GitHub

changes made to the original repo can be updated in the local copy using
'git pull origin main'
